ermediate Advisory Number 21A|url=https://www.nhc.noaa.gov/archive/2019/al09/al092019.public_a.021.shtml?|publisher=National Hurricane Center|date=September 18, 2019|accessdate=December 14, 2019|location=Miami, Florida}}</ref>\n* 09:00&nbsp;UTC (5:00&nbsp;a.m. [[Atlantic Standard Time|AST]]) at {{Coord|14.1|-47.7|name=Tropical Depression Ten strengthens}}&nbsp;\u2013 Tropical Depression Ten strengthens into Tropical Storm Jerry about 960&nbsp;mi (1545&nbsp;km) east of the [[Leeward Islands]].<ref>{{cite report|author=Dave Roberts|title=Tropical Storm Jerry Advisory Number 4|url=https://www.nhc.noaa.gov/archive/2019/al10/al102019.public.004.shtml?|publisher=National Hurricane Center|date=September 19, 2019|accessdate=January 10, 2020|location=Miami, Florida}}</ref>\n\n'''September&nbsp;19'''\n* 21:00 UTC (5:00&nbsp;p.m. [[Atlantic Standard Time|AST]]) at {{Coord|38.5|-58.7|name=Hurricane Humberto weakens}}&nbsp;\u2013 Hurricane Humberto weakens into a Category 2 hurricane roughly 550&nbsp;mi (885&nbsp;km) northeast of [[Bermuda]].<ref>{{cite report|author=John Cangialosi|title=Hurricane Humberto Advisory Number 29|url=https://www.nhc.noaa.gov/archive/2019/al09/al092019.public.029.shtml?|publisher=National Hurricane Center|date=September 19, 2019|accessdate=December 14, 2019|location=Miami, Florida}}</ref>\n* 15:00&nbsp;UTC (11:00&nbsp;a.m. [[Atlantic Standard Time|AST]]) at {{Coord|16.8|-54.4|name=Tropical Storm Jerry strengthens}}&nbsp;\u2013 Tropical Storm Jerry intesifies into a Category 1 hurricane roughly 490&nbsp;mi (785&nbsp;km) east of the [[Leeward Islands]].<ref>{{cite report|author=Eric Blake|title=Hurricane Jerry Advisory Number 9|url=https://www.nhc.noaa.gov/archive/2019/al10/al102019.public.009.shtml?|publisher=National Hurricane Center|date=September 19, 2019|accessdate=January 10, 2020|location=Miami, Florida}}</ref>\n* 21:00&nbsp;UTC (4:00&nbsp;p.m. [[Central Daylight Time|CDT]]) at {{Coord|31.4|-96.4|name=Tropical Depression Imelda}}&nbsp;\u2013 Tropical Depression Imelda weakens into an open wave of remnants roughly 130&nbsp;mi (210&nbsp;km) north-northwest of [[Houston, Texas]].<ref>{{cite report|author1=Gregg Gallina|author2=Frank Pereira|title=Remnants Of Imelda Advisory Number 10|url=https://www.nhc.noaa.gov/archive/2019/al11/al112019.public.010.shtml?|publisher=National Hurricane Center|date=September 19, 2019|accessdate=January 10, 2020|location=Miami, Florida}}</ref>\n\n'''September&nbsp;20'''\n* 03:00&nbsp;UTC (11:00&nbsp;p.m. [[Atlantic Standard Time|AST]] September&nbsp;19) at {{Coord|40.0|-58.0|name=Hurricane Humberto becomes extratropical}}&nbsp;\u2013 Hurricane Humberto transitions into an extratropical cyclone roughly 525&nbsp;mi (845&nbsp;km) south-southwest of [[Cape Race, Newfoundland]].<ref>{{cite report|author=Richard Pasch|title=Post-Tropical Cyclone Humberto Advisory Number 30|url=https://www.nhc.noaa.gov/archive/2019/al09/al092019.public.030.shtml?|publisher=National Hurricane Center|date=September 20, 2019|accessdate=December 14, 2019|location=Miami, Florida}}</ref>\n* 03:00&nbsp;UTC (11:00&nbsp;p.m. [[Atlantic Standard Time|AST]] September&nbsp;19) at {{Coord|18.0|-57.2|name=Hurricane Jerry strengthens}}&nbsp;\u2013 Hurricane Jerry intensifies into a Category 2 hurricane roughly 385&nbsp;mi (625&nbsp;km) east of the northern [[Leeward Islands]].<ref>{{cite report|author=Richard Pasch|title=Hurricane Jerry Advisory Number 11|url=https://www.nhc.noaa.gov/archive/2019/al10/al102019.public.011.shtml?|publisher=National Hurricane Center|date=September 20, 2019|accessdate=January 10, 2020|location=Miami, Florida}}</ref>\n* 15:00&nbsp;UTC (11:00&nbsp;a.m. [[Atlantic Standard Time|AST]]) at {{Coord|18.8|-60.3|name=Hurricane Jerry weakens}}&nbsp;\u2013 Hurricane Jerry weakens into a Category 1 hurricane roughly 130&nbsp;mi (205&nbsp;km) northeast of [[Barbuda]] and 190&nbsp;mi (300&nbsp;km) east-northeast of [[Anguilla]].<ref>{{cite report|author=Eric Blake|title=Hurricane Jerry Advisory Number 13|url=https://www.nhc.noaa.gov/archive/2019/al10/al102019.public.013.shtml?|publisher=National Hurricane Center|date=September 20, 2019|accessdate=January 10, 2020|location=Miami, Florida}}</ref>\n\n'''September&nbsp;21'''\n* 06:00&nbsp;UTC (2:00&nbsp;a.m. [[Atlantic Standard Time|AST]]) at {{Coord|21.0|-63.5|name=Hurricane Jerry weakens}}&nbsp;\u2013 Hurricane Jerry weakens into a tropical storm roughly 240&nbsp;mi (385&nbsp;km) northeast of [[San Juan, Puerto Rico]] and 260&nbsp;mi (420&nbsp;km) north-northwest of [[Anguilla]].<ref>{{cite report|author=Stacy Stewart|title=Tropical Storm Jerry Intermediate Advisory Number 15A|url=https://www.nhc.noaa.gov/archive/2019/al10/al102019.public_a.015.shtml?|publisher=National Hurricane Center|date=September 21, 2019|accessdate=January 10, 2020|location=Miami, Florida}}</ref>\n\n'''September&nbsp;22'''\n* 03:00&nbsp;UTC (11:00&nbsp;p.m. [[Atlantic Standard Time|AST]] September&nbsp;21) at {{Coord|10.8|-20.9|name=Tropical Depression Thirteen forms}}&nbsp;\u2013 Tropical Depression Thirteen forms roughly 365&nbsp;mi (585&nbsp;km) east-southeast of the [[Sotavento Islands|southernmost islands]] of [[Cape Verde]].<ref>{{cite report|author=Jack Beven|title=Tropical Depression Thirteen Advisory Number 1|url=https://www.nhc.noaa.gov/archive/2019/al13/al132019.public.001.shtml?|publisher=National Hurricane Center|date=September 22, 2019|accessdate=January 10, 2020|location=Miami, Florida}}</ref>\n* 09:00&nbsp;UTC (5:00&nbsp;a.m. [[Atlantic Standard Time|AST]]) at {{Coord|11.9|-60.2|name=Tropical Storm Karen forms}}&nbsp;\u2013 Tropical Storm Karen forms roughly 100&nbsp;mi (165&nbsp;km) east of [[Grenada]] and 120&nbsp;mi (190&nbsp;km) southeast of [[Saint Vincent (Antilles)|Saint Vincent]].<ref>{{cite report|author=Stacy Stewart|title=Tropical Storm Karen Advisory Number 1|url=https://www.nhc.noaa.gov/archive/2019/al12/al122019.public.001.shtml?|publisher=National Hurricane Center|date=September 22, 2019|accessdate=January 11, 2020|location=Miami, Florida}}</ref>\n\n'''September&nbsp;23'''\n* 15:00&nbsp;UTC (11:00&nbsp;a.m. [[Atlantic Standard Time|AST]]) at {{Coord|11.1|-24.1|name=Tropical Depression Thirteen strengthens}}&nbsp;\u2013 Tropical Depression Thirteen strengthens into Tropical Storm Lorenzo roughly 255&nbsp;mi (410&nbsp;km) south of the [[Sotavento Islands|southernmost islands]] of [[Cape Verde]].<ref>{{cite report|author=David Zelinsky|title=Tropical Storm Lorenzo Advisory Number 3...Corrected|url=https://www.nhc.noaa.gov/archive/2019/al13/al132019.public.003.shtml?|publisher=National Hurricane Center|date=September 23, 2019|accessdate=January 12, 2020|location=Miami, Florida}}</ref>\n* 21:00&nbsp;UTC (5:00&nbsp;p.m. [[Atlantic Standard Time|AST]]) at {{Coord|15.9|-65.6|name=Tropical Storm Karen weakens}}&nbsp;\u2013 Tropical Storm Karen weakens into a tropical depression roughly 135&nbsp;mi (215&nbsp;km) south-southwest of [[Saint Croix]] and 175&nbsp;mi (285&nbsp;km) south of [[San Juan, Puerto Rico]].<ref>{{cite report|author=Daniel Brown|title=Tropical Depression Karen Advisory Number 7|url=https://www.nhc.noaa.gov/archive/2019/al12/al122019.public.007.shtml?|publisher=National Hurricane Center|date=September 23, 2019|accessdate=January 11, 2020|location=Miami, Florida}}</ref>\n\n'''September&nbsp;24'''\n* 09:00&nbsp;UTC (5:00&nbsp;a.m. [[Atlantic Standard Time|AST]]) at {{Coord|16.8|-65.8|name=Tropical Depression Karen strengthens}}&nbsp;\u2013 Tropical Depression Karen strengthens into a tropical storm roughly 90&nbsp;mi (145&nbsp;km) southwest of [[Saint Croix]] and 110&nbsp;mi (180&nbsp;km) south of [[San Juan, Puerto Rico]].<ref>{{cite report|author=Stacy Stewart|title=Tropical Storm Karen Advisory Number 9|url=https://www.nhc.noaa.gov/archive/2019/al12/al122019.public.009.shtml?|publisher=National Hurricane Center|date=September 24, 2019|accessdate=January 11, 2020|location=Miami, Florida}}</ref>\n\n'''September&nbsp;25'''\n* 09:00&nbsp;UTC (5:00&nbsp;a.m. [[Atlantic Standard Time|AST]]) at {{Coord|31.8|-67.9|name=Tropical Storm Jerry becomes post-tropical}}&nbsp;\u2013 Tropical Storm Jerry becomes a post-tropical cyclone roughly 185&nbsp;mi (295&nbsp;km) west of [[Bermuda]].<ref>{{cite report|author=David Zelinsky|title=Post-Tropical Cyclone Jerry Advisory Number 32|url=https://www.nhc.noaa.gov/archive/2019/al10/al102019.public.032.shtml?|publisher=National Hurricane Center|date=September 25, 2019|accessdate=January 10, 2020|location=Miami, Florida}}</ref>\n* 09:00&nbsp;UTC (5:00&nbsp;a.m. [[Atlantic Standard Time|AST]]) at {{Coord|13.6|-33.9|name=Tropical Storm Lorenzo strengthens}}&nbsp;\u2013 Tropical Storm Lorenzo becomes a Category 1 hurricane roughly 640&nbsp;mi (1030&nbsp;km) west of the [[Sotavento Islands|southernmost islands]] of [[Cape Verde]].<ref>{{cite report|author1=David Zelinsky|author2=Nelsie Ramos|title=Hurricane Lorenzo Advisory Number 10|url=https://www.nhc.noaa.gov/archive/2019/al13/al132019.public.010.shtml?|publisher=National Hurricane Center|date=September 25, 2019|accessdate=January 12, 2020|location=Miami, Florida}}</ref>\n\n'''September&nbsp;26'''\n* 03:00&nbsp;UTC (11:00&nbsp;p.m. [[Atlantic Standard Time|AST]] September&nbsp;25) at {{Coord|14.7|-38.1|name=Hurricane Lorenzo strengthens}}&nbsp;\u2013 Hurricane Lorenzo strengthens into a Category 2 hurricane roughly 915&nbsp;mi (1470&nbsp;km) west of the [[Sotavento Islands|southernmost islands]] of [[Cape Verde]].<ref>{{cite report|author=Andrew Latto|title=Hurricane Lorenzo Advisory Number 13|url=https://www.nhc.noaa.gov/archive/2019/al13/al132019.public.013.shtml?|publisher=National Hurricane Center|date=September 26, 2019|accessdate=January 12, 2020|location=Miami, Florida}}</ref>\n* 10:00&nbsp;UTC (6:00&nbsp;a.m. [[Atlantic Standard Time|AST]]) at {{Coord|15.2|-39.3|name=Hurricane Lorenzo becomes a major hurricane}}&nbsp;\u2013 Hurricane Lorenzo becomes a major hurricane roughly 995&nbsp;mi (1600&nbsp;km) west of the [[Sotavento Islands|southernmost islands]] of [[Cape Verde]].<ref>{{cite report|author=David Zelinsky|title=Hurricane Lorenzo Special Advisory Number 15|url=https://www.nhc.noaa.gov/archive/2019/al13/al132019.public.015.shtml?|publisher=National Hurricane Center|date=September 26, 2019|accessdate=January 12, 2020|location=Miami, Florida}}</ref>\n* 15:00&nbsp;UTC (11:00&nbsp;a.m. [[Atlantic Standard Time|AST]]) at {{Coord|15.4|-40.2|name=Hurricane Lorenzo strengthens}}&nbsp;\u2013 Hurricane Lorenzo strengthens into a Category 4 hurricane roughly 1055&nbsp;mi (1695&nbsp;km) west of the [[Sotavento Islands|southernmost islands]] of [[Cape Verde]].<ref>{{cite report|author=Jack Beven|title=Hurricane Lorenzo Advisory Number 16|url=https://www.nhc.noaa.gov/archive/2019/al13/al132019.public.016.shtml?|publisher=National Hurricane Center|date=September 26, 2019|accessdate=January 12, 2020|location=Miami, Florida}}</ref>\n\n'''September&nbsp;27'''\n* 15:00&nbsp;UTC (11:00&nbsp;a.m. [[Atlantic Standard Time|AST]]) at {{Coord|28.8|-59.6|name=Tropical Storm Karen weakens}}&nbsp;\u2013 Tropical Storm Karen weakens into a tropical depression again roughly 390&nbsp;mi (630&nbsp;km) southeast of [[Bermuda]].<ref>{{cite report|author=Robbie Berg|title=Tropical Depression Karen Advisory Number 22|url=https://www.nhc.noaa.gov/archive/2019/al12/al122019.public.022.shtml?|publisher=National Hurricane Center|date=September 27, 2019|accessdate=January 11, 2020|location=Miami, Florida}}</ref>\n* 21:00&nbsp;UTC (5:00&nbsp;p.m. [[Atlantic Standard Time|AST]]) at {{Coord|29.3|-58.5|name=Tropical Depression Karen degenerates}}&nbsp;\u2013 Tropical Depression Karen degenerates into a surface trough roughly 425&nbsp;mi (685&nbsp;km) east-southeast of [[Bermuda]].<ref>{{cite report|author=Robbie Berg|title=Remnants Of Karen Advisory Number 23|url=https://www.nhc.noaa.gov/archive/2019/al12/al122019.public.023.shtml?|publisher=National Hurricane Center|date=September 27, 2019|accessdate=January 11, 2020|location=Miami, Florida}}</ref>\n* 21:00&nbsp;UTC (5:00&nbsp;p.m. [[Atlantic Standard Time|AST]]) at {{Coord|20.3|-43.6|name=Hurricane Lorenzo weakens}}&nbsp;\u2013 Hurricane Lorenzo weakens into a Category 3 hurricane roughly 1575&nbsp;mi (2535&nbsp;km) southwest of the [[Azores]].<ref>{{cite report|author=Jack Beven|title=Hurricane Lorenzo Advisory Number 21|url=https://www.nhc.noaa.gov/archive/2019/al13/al132019.public.021.shtml?|publisher=National Hurricane Center|date=September 27, 2019|accessdate=January 12, 2020|location=Miami, Florida}}</ref>\n\n'''September&nbsp;28'''\n* 21:00&nbsp;UTC (5:00&nbsp;p.m. [[Atlantic Standard Time|AST]]) at {{Coord|23.3|-45.0|name=Hurricane Lorenzo strengthens}}&nbsp;\u2013 Hurricane Lorenzo restrengthens into a Category 4 hurricane roughly 1470&nbsp;mi (2365&nbsp;km) southwest of the [[Azores]].<ref>{{cite report|author=Robbie Berg|title=Hurricane Lorenzo Advisory Number 25|url=https://www.nhc.noaa.gov/archive/2019/al13/al132019.public.025.shtml?|publisher=National Hurricane Center|date=September 28, 2019|accessdate=January 12, 2020|location=Miami, Florida}}</ref>\n\n'''September&nbsp;29'''\n* 02:10&nbsp;UTC (10:10&nbsp;p.m. [[Atlantic Standard Time|AST]]) at {{Coord|24.1|-45.0|name=Hurricane Lorenzo strengthens}}&nbsp;\u2013 Hurricane Lorenzo strengthens into a Category 5 hurricane roughly 1410&nbsp;mi (2270&nbsp;km) southwest of the [[Azores]].<ref>{{cite report|author1=Daniel Brown|author2=Andrew Latto|title=Hurricane Lorenzo Tropical Cyclone Update|url=https://www.nhc.noaa.gov/archive/2019/al13/al132019.update.09290207.shtml?|publisher=National Hurricane Center|date=September 29, 2019|accessdate=January 12, 2020|location=Miami, Florida}}</ref>\n* 18:00&nbsp;UTC (2:00&nbsp;p.m. [[Atlantic Standard Time|AST]]) at {{Coord|26.4|-44.4|name=Hurricane Lorenzo Continues to weaken}}&nbsp;- Hurricane Lorenzo continues to weaken over open ocean to a Category 2 Hurricane with 90knot sustained winds roughly 1372&nbsp;mi (2207&nbsp;km) southwest of the [[Azores]].<ref>{{cite report|author=David A. Zelinsky|title= National Hurricane Center Tropical Cyclone Report, Hurricane Lorenzo (AL132019)|url=https://www.nhc.noaa.gov/data/tcr/AL132019_Lorenzo.pdf|publisher= National Hurricane Center (NHC)|date=December 16, 2019|accessdate=April 3, 2020|location=Miami, Florida}}</ref>\n\n===October===\n===November===\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|Tropical cyclones}}\n*[[2019 Atlantic hurricane season]]\n*[[List of Atlantic hurricanes]]\n*[[Timeline of the 2019 Pacific hurricane season]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|2019 Atlantic hurricane season}}\n* The [[National Hurricane Center|National Hurricane Center (NHC)]]'s [http://www.nhc.noaa.gov/archive/2019/ 2019 Tropical Cyclone Advisory Archive]\n\n{{2019 Atlantic hurricane season buttons}}\n{{TC Decades|Year=2010|basin=Atlantic|type=hurricane}}\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{Succession box|before=[[Timeline of the 2018 Atlantic hurricane season|2018]]|title=Atlantic hurricane season timelines|years=2019|after=[[Timeline of the 2020 Atlantic hurricane season|2020]]}}{{S-end}}\n\n[[Category:2019 Atlantic hurricane season]]\n[[Category:Atlantic Ocean meteorological timelines]]\n", "text_old": "{{Update|date=September 2019}}\n\n{{Tropical cyclone timeline\n| Track=2019 Atlantic hurricane season summary map.png\n| First date= May 20, 2019\n| Last date= November 25, 2019\n| Average wind speed=1\n| Strongest system= Dorian\n| Winds=160\n| Pressure=910\n| Longest system= Dorian\n| Total days= 14.25\n| Five years= [[Timeline of the 2017 Atlantic hurricane season|2017]], [[Timeline of the 2018 Atlantic hurricane season|2018]], '''2019''', ''2020'', ''2021''\n| Year = 2019\n| Basin = Atl\n| Season = Atlantic hurricane season\n| Storm1= [[Hurricane Barry (2019)]]\n| Storm2= [[Hurricane Dorian]]\n| Storm3= [[Tropical Storm Fernand (2019)]]\n| Storm4= [[Hurricane Humberto (2019)]]\n| Storm5= [[Tropical Storm Imelda]]\n| Storm6= [[Hurricane Lorenzo (2019)]]\n| Storm7= [[Tropical Storm Nestor (2019)]]\n| Storm8= [[Tropical Storm Olga (2019)]]\n| Storm9=\n| Storm10=\n| Storm11=\n| Storm12=\n| Storm13 =\n| Storm14 = \n| Storm15 = \n| Storm16 =\n| Storm17 = \n| Storm18 = \n| Storm19 =\n| Storm20 =\n| Storm21 =\n| Storm22 =\n| Storm23 =\n| Storm24 =\n| Storm25 =\n}}\nThe [[2019 Atlantic hurricane season]] was an event in the annual [[tropical cyclone]] season in the North Hemisphere. The season officially began on June&nbsp;1, 2019 and ended on November&nbsp;30, 2019. These dates, adopted by convention, historically describe the period in each year when most systems form.<ref name=\"SeasonDates\">{{cite book|url=http://www.aoml.noaa.gov/hrd/tcfaq/tcfaqHED.html|title=Hurricane Research Division: Frequently Asked Questions|chapter=G: Tropical Cyclone Climatology|chapterurl=http://www.aoml.noaa.gov/hrd/tcfaq/tcfaqG.html|at=[http://www.aoml.noaa.gov/hrd/tcfaq/G1.html G1) When is hurricane season ?]|author1=Christopher W. Landsea|author2=Neal Dorst|author3=Erica Rule|work=[[Atlantic Oceanographic and Meteorological Laboratory]]|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|date=June 2, 2011|accessdate=July 1, 2019}}</ref> However, systems can and do form outside these dates, such as Subtropical Storm Andrea, which formed on May&nbsp;20.\n\nThis timeline documents tropical cyclone formations, strengthening, weakening, [[Landfall (meteorology)|landfall]]s, [[Extratropical cyclone#Extratropical transition|extratropical transitions]], and dissipations during the season. It includes information that was not released throughout the season, meaning that data from post-storm reviews by the [[National Hurricane Center]], such as a storm that was not initially warned upon, has been included.\n\n== Timeline of events ==\n<center>\n<timeline>\nImageSize = width:800 height:215\nPlotArea  = top:10 bottom:80 right:20 left:20\nLegend    = columns:3 left:30 top:58 columnwidth:270\nAlignBars = early\n\nDateFormat = dd/mm/yyyy\nPeriod     = f