{"title_page": "Nordh\u00fcmmling", "text_new": "{{Infobox German location\n|type = Samtgemeinde\n|name = Nordh\u00fcmmling\n|name_local = \n|image_coa = DEU SG Nordhuemmling COA.png\n|state = [[Lower Saxony]] \n|regbzk = \n|district = [[Emsland]]\n|population = 12149\n|population_as_of = 2005<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20060211031848/http://www.nls.niedersachsen.de/Download/StatistischeBerichte/AI2_hj1_2005Gesamt.pdf source]</ref>\n|Gemeindeschl\u00fcssel = 034545406\n|area = 142.63\n|elevation = 13\n|coordinates = {{coord|52|58|N|7|37|E|format=dms|display=inline,title}}\n|image_plan = Samtgemeinde Nordh\u00fcmmling in EL.svg\n|postal_code = \n|area_code = \n|licence = EL\n|mayor = Hermann Tebben\n|website = {{url|https://sg-nordhuemmling.de/}}\n}}\n'''Nordh\u00fcmmling''' is a ''[[Samtgemeinde]]'' in the district [[Emsland]] in [[Lower Saxony]], [[Germany]].\n\nThe following towns are situated in Nordh\u00fcmmling:\n\n(Population 2005)\n{|\n|-\n|valign=\"top\" |\n[[Image:Samtgemeinde Nordhuemmling.png|180px]]\n|valign=\"top\" |\n# [[Bockhorst]] (1010)\n# [[Breddenberg]] (791)\n# [[Esterwegen]] (5129)\n# [[Hilkenbrook]] (817)\n# [[Surwold]] (4402)\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Nordhummling}}\n[[Category:Samtgemeinden in Lower Saxony]]\n\n\n{{emsland-geo-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox German location\n|type = Samtgemeinde\n|name = Nordh\u00fcmmling\n|name_local = \n|image_coa = DEU SG Nordhuemmling COA.png\n|state = [[Lower Saxony]] \n|regbzk = \n|district = [[Emsland]]\n|population = 12149\n|population_as_of = 2005\n|population_ref = [https://web.archive.org/web/20060211031848/http://www.nls.niedersachsen.de/Download/StatistischeBerichte/AI2_hj1_2005Gesamt.pdf source]\n|Gemeindeschl\u00fcssel = 034545406\n|pop_dens = 85\n|area = 142.63\n|elevation = 13\n|coordinates = {{coord|52|58|N|7|37|E|format=dms|display=inline,title}}\n|lat_hem = N\n|lon_hem = E\n|image_plan = Samtgemeinde Nordh\u00fcmmling in EL.svg\n|postal_code = \n|area_code = \n|licence = EL\n|mayor = Hermann Tebben\n|website = [https://web.archive.org/web/20020126040940/http://www.nordhuemmling.de/ nordhuemmling.de]\n}}\n'''Nordh\u00fcmmling''' is a ''[[Samtgemeinde]]'' in the district [[Emsland]] in [[Lower Saxony]], [[Germany]].\n\nThe following towns are situated in Nordh\u00fcmmling:\n\n(Population 2005)\n{|\n|-\n|valign=\"top\" |\n[[Image:Samtgemeinde Nordhuemmling.png|180px]]\n|valign=\"top\" |\n# [[Bockhorst]] (1010)\n# [[Breddenberg]] (791)\n# [[Esterwegen]] (5129)\n# [[Hilkenbrook]] (817)\n# [[Surwold]] (4402)\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Nordhummling}}\n[[Category:Samtgemeinden in Lower Saxony]]\n\n\n{{emsland-geo-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Markussep", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nordh%C3%BCmmling"}
{"title_page": "Grays Harbor", "text_new": "[[File:GraysHarbor.png|thumb|right|300px|Map of Grays Harbor]]'''Grays Harbor''' is an [[estuary|estuarine]] bay located {{convert|45|mi|km}} north of the mouth of the [[Columbia River]], on the southwest [[Pacific]] coast of [[Washington (U.S. state)|Washington]] state, in the [[United States of America]].  It is a [[ria]], which formed at the end of the last ice age, when sea levels flooded the [[Chehalis River (Washington)|Chehalis River]]. The bay is {{convert|17|mi|km}} long and {{convert|12|mi|km}} wide.<ref name=gulick164>{{cite book |title=A Traveler's History of Washington |last=Gulick |first=Bill |year=1996 |publisher=Caxton Press |location=[[Caldwell, Idaho]] |isbn=978-0-87004-371-0 |page=164}}</ref>  The [[Chehalis River (Washington)|Chehalis River]] flows into its eastern end, where the city of [[Aberdeen, Washington|Aberdeen]] stands at that river's mouth, on its north bank, with the somewhat smaller city of [[Hoquiam, Washington|Hoquiam]] immediately to its northwest, along the bayshore.  Besides the Chehalis, many lesser rivers and streams flow into Grays Harbor, such as [[Hoquiam River]] and [[Humptulips River]].  A pair of low peninsulas separate it from the Pacific Ocean, except for an opening about two miles (3&nbsp;km) in width.  The northern peninsula, which is largely covered by the community of [[Ocean Shores, Washington|Ocean Shores]], ends in Point Brown.  Facing that across the bay-mouth is Point Chehalis, at the end of the southern peninsula upon which stands the town of [[Westport, Washington|Westport]].\n\nGrays Harbor is named after Captain [[Robert Gray (sea-captain)|Robert Gray]]<ref name=gulick164/> who discovered and entered it on May 7, 1792 in the course of his fur-trading voyages along the north Pacific coast of North America.  Gray named the bay Bullfinch Harbor, but it was afterward named Gray's Harbor by Captain [[George Vancouver]], whose contemporaneous explorations of the region\u2014the ships of the two captains had met at sea, only days earlier\u2014were well publicised at the time, while Gray's voyages were not. Gray's Harbor was the name that stuck (the apostrophe was omitted under [[United States Board on Geographic Names|US Board on Geographic Names]] guidelines). A few days later, on May 11 Gray found a navigable channel into the estuary of the Columbia River, and [[Robert Gray's Columbia River expedition|sailed into it]], the first white man known to have done so.<ref name=\"OP\">{{cite web\n  | last = Flora\n  | first = Stephenie \n  | authorlink = \n  | title = Captain Robert Gray\n  | website = \n  | publisher = OregonPioneers.com\n  | date = \n  | url =  http://www.oregonpioneers.com/gray.htm\n  | doi = \n  | accessdate = 2006-12-11 }}\n</ref>\n\nSettlement of the area began in the early 1870s and was largely dependent on the [[lumber]] industry. As the [[forest]]s of the [[eastern United States]] depleted, many [[logging|loggers]] from the East and the [[Midwestern United States|Midwest]] migrated to the Grays Harbor area, as well as many [[Scandinavia]]ns and [[Finland|Finns]] from [[Europe]].<ref>Gulick 1996, pp. 164-165.</ref>\n\n[[Grays Harbor National Wildlife Refuge]] is located on {{convert|1500|acre|km2}} of intertidal mudflats, salt marsh, and uplands around Hoquiam.\n\nThe ''Daily Washingtonian'' was a daily newspaper in Grays Harbor founded by Otis M. Moore.\n\n==Islands and sandbars==\nIslands include:\n*Grass Island ({{coord|46|52|34|N|124|05|27|W}}), near Westport\n*[[Rennie Island]], near Aberdeen, the largest at {{convert|225|acres}}\n*[[Sand Island (Washington)|Sand Island]], almost in the center of Grays Harbor\n**Goose Island ({{coord|46|58|38|N|124|04|13|W}}),<ref>{{GNIS|1505192|Goose Island, Grays Harbor County, Washington}}</ref> near Sand Island\n\nProtection Island ({{coord|46|56|39|N|124|07|34|W}}) is listed by USGS,<ref>{{GNIS|1513026|Protection Island, Grays Harbor County, Washington}}</ref> but {{as of|2018|lc=yes}} is listed by the City of Ocean Shores as an accreted landform called Damon Point, a {{convert|61|acre|adj=on}} park attached to Point Brown.<ref>{{citation|title=Damon Point|publisher=City of Ocean Shores|url=http://cityofoceanshores.com/damon-point-beach-ocean-shores/|accessdate=2018-05-17}}</ref>\n\nNamed bars include Whitcomb Flats ({{coord|46|54|39|N|124|04|54|W}}), near Westport.<ref>{{GNIS|1509459|Whitcomb Flats}}</ref> A large unnamed bar or island ({{coord|46.911|N|124.007|W}}) also stands off of [[Markham, Washington|Markham]] at the mouth of [[Johns River (Washington)|Johns River]].<ref>USGS 1:24,000 \"Westport, Washington\" topographic quadrangle, 1995 ed.</ref>\n\nSand Island, Goose Island and Whitcomb Flats are included in [[Washington Natural Areas Program]].<ref>{{citation|title=List of Natural Area Preserves in Grays Harbor County|publisher=[[Washington Department of Natural Resources]]|url=https://www.dnr.wa.gov/managed-lands/natural-areas/natural-area-preserves|accessdate=2018-05-17}}</ref> Johns River Wildlife Area, managed by [[Washington State Department of Fish and Wildlife]], includes the Markham island.<ref>{{cite web|website=WDFW Lands (official website)|title=Johns River Wildlife Area|publisher=[[Washington State Department of Fish and Wildlife]]|url=https://wdfw.wa.gov/lands/wildlife_areas/johns_river/}}</ref>\n\n==Historic events==\nIn the early 20th century, Greys Harbor was the largest lumber shipyard in the world.<ref>{{cite magazine |last=Lockley |first=Fred |date=June 1907 |title=Grays Harbor: The Largest Lumber-Shipping Port in the World |magazine=[[The Pacific Monthly]]}}</ref> The [[Industrial Workers of the World]] led strikes in the area in 1912, 1917, and 1923. Some of these labor actions were militant, such as an armed union ship shooting at the ''Fearless'', a scab ship in 1906.<ref>{{cite thesis |last=Goings |first=Aaron |date=2005 |title=Red Harbor: Class, Violence, and Community in Grays Harbor, Washington |type=PhD |publisher=Simon Fraser University ||citeseerx=10.1.1.825.1081 }}</ref>\n\n[[File:Gray's Harbor, from Hoquiam.png|thumb|Grays Harbor in 1891 (or earlier?), as depicted in [[Frances Fuller Victor]]'s ''Atlantis Arisen''.]]\nThe schooner ''[[Annie Larsen]]'' was seized at Grays Harbor on 25 June 1915 by US customs officials, later leading to what was at the time the most expensive [[Annie Larsen affair#Trial|trial]] in US legal history.\n\nDuring World War II, harbor defenses including searchlights, [[12-inch coast defense mortar]], 155&nbsp;mm howitzers and other guns were emplaced around Grays Harbor by [[Western Defense Command]] (see [[56th Air Defense Artillery Regiment]]).<ref>{{citation|title=Modern American seacoast defenses \u2013 a list of military reservations and concrete gun batteries 1890-1950|first=Mark A. |last=Berhow|publisher=Coast Defense Study Group|date=February 1, 2017|url=http://cdsg.org/wp-content/uploads/pdfs/CDSG/CDSG%20WEBSITE%20UPDATES/CDSG%20Downloads/CDList12.pdf}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n== External links ==\n*[http://www.topozone.com/map.asp?lat=46.95083&lon=-124.04972&datum=nad27&u=4&layer=DRG&size=l&s=1000 Topographic map]\n\n{{Coord|46|57|02|N|124|03|04|W|type:waterbody_scale:250000_region:US-WA|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Bays of Washington (state)]]\n[[Category:Bodies of water of Grays Harbor County, Washington]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:GraysHarbor.png|thumb|right|300px|Map of Grays Harbor]]'''Grays Harbor''' is an [[estuary|estuarine]] bay located {{convert|45|mi|km}} north of the mouth of the [[Columbia River]], on the southwest [[Pacific]] coast of [[Washington (U.S. state)|Washington]] state, in the [[United States of America]].  It is a [[ria]], which formed at the end of the last ice age, when sea levels flooded the [[Chehalis River (Washington)|Chehalis River]]. The bay is {{convert|17|mi|km}} long and {{convert|12|mi|km}} wide.<ref name=gulick164>{{cite book |title=A Traveler's History of Washington |last=Gulick |first=Bill |year=1996 |publisher=Caxton Press |location=[[Caldwell, Idaho]] |isbn=978-0-87004-371-0 |page=164}}</ref>  The [[Chehalis River (Washington)|Chehalis River]] flows into its eastern end, where the city of [[Aberdeen, Washington|Aberdeen]] stands at that river's mouth, on its north bank, with the somewhat smaller city of [[Hoquiam, Washington|Hoquiam]] immediately to its northwest, along the bayshore.  Besides the Chehalis, many lesser rivers and streams flow into Grays Harbor, such as [[Hoquiam River]] and [[Humptulips River]].  A pair of low peninsulas separate it from the Pacific Ocean, except for an opening about two miles (3&nbsp;km) in width.  The northern peninsula, which is largely covered by the community of [[Ocean Shores, Washington|Ocean Shores]], ends in Point Brown.  Facing that across the bay-mouth is Point Chehalis, at the end of the southern peninsula upon which stands the town of [[Westport, Washington|Westport]].\n\nGrays Harbor is named after Captain [[Robert Gray (sea-captain)|Robert Gray]]<ref name=gulick164/> who discovered and entered it on May 7, 1792 in the course of his fur-trading voyages along the north Pacific coast of North America.  Gray named the bay Bullfinch Harbor, but it was afterward named Gray's Harbor by Captain [[George Vancouver]], whose contemporaneous explorations of the region\u2014the ships of the two captains had met at sea, only days earlier\u2014were well publicised at the time, while Gray's voyages were not. Gray's Harbor was the name that stuck (the apostrophe was omitted under [[United States Board on Geographic Names|US Board on Geographic Names]] guidelines). A few days later, on May 11 Gray found a navigable channel into the estuary of the Columbia River, and [[Robert Gray's Columbia River expedition|sailed into it]], the first white man known to have done so.<ref name=\"OP\">{{cite web\n  | last = Flora\n  | first = Stephenie \n  | authorlink = \n  | title = Captain Robert Gray\n  | website = \n  | publisher = OregonPioneers.com\n  | date = \n  | url =  http://www.oregonpioneers.com/gray.htm\n  | doi = \n  | accessdate = 2006-12-11 }}\n</ref>\n\nSettlement of the area began in the early 1870s and was largely dependent on the [[lumber]] industry. As the [[forest]]s of the [[eastern United States]] depleted, many [[logging|loggers]] from the East and the [[Midwestern United States|Midwest]] migrated to the Grays Harbor area, as well as many [[Scandinavia]]ns and [[Finland|Finns]] from [[Europe]].<ref>Gulick 1996, pp. 164-165.</ref>\n\n[[Grays Harbor National Wildlife Refuge]] is located on {{convert|1500|acre|km2}} of intertidal mudflats, salt marsh, and uplands around Hoquiam.\n\nThe ''Daily Washingtonian'' was a daily newspaper in Grays Harbor founded by Otis M. Moore.\n\n==Islands and sandbars==\nIslands include:\n*Grass Island ({{coord|46|52|34|N|124|05|27|W}}), near Westport\n*[[Rennie Island]], near Aberdeen, the largest at {{convert|225|acres}}\n*[[Sand Island (Washington)|Sand Island]], almost in the center of Grays Harbor\n**Goose Island ({{coord|46|58|38|N|124|04|13|W}}),<ref>{{GNIS|1505192|Goose Island, Grays Harbor County, Washington}}</ref> near Sand Island\n\nProtection Island ({{coord|46|56|39|N|124|07|34|W}}) is listed by USGS,<ref>{{GNIS|1513026|Protection Island, Grays Harbor County, Washington}}</ref> but {{as of|2018|lc=yes}} is listed by the City of Ocean Shores as an accreted landform called Damon Point, a {{convert|61|acre|adj=on}} park attached to Point Brown.<ref>{{citation|title=Damon Point|publisher=City of Ocean Shores|url=http://cityofoceanshores.com/damon-point-beach-ocean-shores/|accessdate=2018-05-17}}</ref>\n\nNamed bars include Whitcomb Flats ({{coord|46|54|39|N|124|04|54|W}}), near Westport.<ref>{{GNIS|1509459|Whitcomb Flats}}</ref> A large unnamed bar or island ({{coord|46.911|N|124.007|W}}) also stands off of [[Markham, Washington|Markham]] at the mouth of [[Johns River (Washington)|Johns River]].<ref>USGS 1:24,000 \"Westport, Washington\" topographic quadrangle, 1995 ed.</ref>\n\nSand Island, Goose Island and Whitcomb Flats are included in [[Washington Natural Areas Program]].<ref>{{citation|title=List of Natural Area Preserves in Grays Harbor County|publisher=[[Washington Department of Natural Resources]]|url=https://www.dnr.wa.gov/managed-lands/natural-areas/natural-area-preserves|accessdate=2018-05-17}}</ref> Johns River Wildlife Area, managed by [[Washington State Department of Fish and Wildlife]], includes the Markham island.<ref>{{cite web|website=WDFW Lands (official website)|title=Johns River Wildlife Area|publisher=[[Washington State Department of Fish and Wildlife]]|url=https://wdfw.wa.gov/lands/wildlife_areas/johns_river/}}</ref>\n\n==Historic events==\nIn the early 20th century, Greys Harbor was the largest lumber shipyard in the world.<ref>{{cite magazine |last=Lockley |first=Fred |date=June 1907 |title=Grays Harbor: The Largest Lumber-Shipping Port in the World |magazine=[[The Pacific Monthly]] |</ref> The [[Industrial Workers of the World]] led strikes in the area in 1912, 1917, and 1923. Some of these labor actions were militant, such as an armed union ship shooting at the ''Fearless'', a scab ship in 1906.<ref>{{cite thesis |last=Goings |first=Aaron |date=2005 |title=Red Harbor: Class, Violence, and Community in Grays Harbor, Washington |type=PhD |publisher=Simon Fraser University ||citeseerx=10.1.1.825.1081 }}</ref>\n\n[[File:Gray's Harbor, from Hoquiam.png|thumb|Grays Harbor in 1891 (or earlier?), as depicted in [[Frances Fuller Victor]]'s ''Atlantis Arisen''.]]\nThe schooner ''[[Annie Larsen]]'' was seized at Grays Harbor on 25 June 1915 by US customs officials, later leading to what was at the time the most expensive [[Annie Larsen affair#Trial|trial]] in US legal history.\n\nDuring World War II, harbor defenses including searchlights, [[12-inch coast defense mortar]], 155&nbsp;mm howitzers and other guns were emplaced around Grays Harbor by [[Western Defense Command]] (see [[56th Air Defense Artillery Regiment]]).<ref>{{citation|title=Modern American seacoast defenses \u2013 a list of military reservations and concrete gun batteries 1890-1950|first=Mark A. |last=Berhow|publisher=Coast Defense Study Group|date=February 1, 2017|url=http://cdsg.org/wp-content/uploads/pdfs/CDSG/CDSG%20WEBSITE%20UPDATES/CDSG%20Downloads/CDList12.pdf}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n== External links ==\n*[http://www.topozone.com/map.asp?lat=46.95083&lon=-124.04972&datum=nad27&u=4&layer=DRG&size=l&s=1000 Topographic map]\n\n{{Coord|46|57|02|N|124|03|04|W|type:waterbody_scale:250000_region:US-WA|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Bays of Washington (state)]]\n[[Category:Bodies of water of Grays Harbor County, Washington]]\n", "name_user": "Grimes2", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eHistoric events:format cite template", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Grays_Harbor"}
